# gleepack is a Gleam packager — builds Gleam apps
# into standalone executables.  Authored by yoshi-
# monster (10 GH stars).  Sister tools: gleam
# (Gleam compiler, already in corpus as `_gleam`),
# gleescript (Gleam-to-Erlang escript builder, NOT
# in corpus — different library), birdie (Gleam
# snapshot testing, NOT in corpus — uses
# handwritten parser, not Glint).
#
# Critical extraction note: gleepack uses **Glint
# pipe-style builder** at gleepack.gleam:22-43 —
# Gleam's `|>` pipe operator chains `glint.new()`
# through a series of `glint.add(at:, do:)` calls.
# Each `|>` step takes the previous Glint value
# and returns a NEW Glint (Gleam's IMMUTABILITY-
# BY-DEFAULT means each step builds a new value
# rather than mutating).  Distinct from R301 Nim
# cligen (proc-signature-as-spec compile-time
# macro), R302 Clojure babashka.cli (vector-of-
# maps data spec), R296 Julia Comonicon (function-
# signature-as-spec compile-time macro), R295 CL
# clingon (CLOS subclassing), R290 Racket
# `command-line` (s-expression DSL macro), and
# R287 Nim parseopt (manual `for kind, key, val`
# loop).  Glint's approach: CHAINED PIPE-BUILDER
# with NAMED ARGUMENTS (Gleam's `at:` and `do:`
# label syntax).  Sister to Haskell's
# `optparse-applicative <**>` chain (R270) — but
# Glint uses GLEAM PIPE (`|>`) rather than the
# applicative `<*>`.  Documents the **chained-
# pipe-builder-with-named-args CLI pattern** —
# Gleam-specific.  Extends cross-language CLI
# taxonomy to FORTY-TWO library variants: Rust (6),
# Go (4), Python (3), Crystal 1 (R269),
# Haskell (R270), OCaml (R271), C (R272),
# Java (R276), Kotlin (R277), Scala (R278),
# Dart (R279), Ruby (R280), Perl (R281),
# PHP (R282), Swift (R283), F# (R284), Lua (R285),
# C# (R286), Nim 1 parseopt (R287), Zig (R288),
# D (R289), Racket (R290), Common Lisp 1 (R291),
# Erlang (R292), Tcl (R293), Pharo Smalltalk (R294),
# Common Lisp 2 clingon (R295), Julia (R296),
# SWI-Prolog optparse (R297), Pony stdlib cli (R298),
# Crystal 2 Admiral (R299), V stdlib `flag` (R300),
# Nim 2 cligen (R301), Clojure babashka.cli (R302),
# **Gleam Glint** (R303 — NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN
# MILESTONE**: 42 cross-language CLI library
# variants documented.
#
# Critical extraction note: gleepack uses **Gleam
# `use` callback-syntax for flag/command binding**
# at command/build.gleam:19-65 — `use FLAG <-
# glint.flag(SPEC)` is Gleam's CONTINUATION-PASSING-
# STYLE syntax sugar: it desugars to
# `glint.flag(SPEC, fn(FLAG) { REST_OF_BLOCK })`.
# The Glint API uses this so flag SPECS and the
# COMMAND BODY live in the same `pub fn command()`
# block without callback nesting.  Distinct from
# R295 CL clingon's `:options (list (clingon:make-
# option ...))` constructor list, R301 Nim cligen
# (proc-signature-as-spec), R302 Clojure babashka.
# cli (vector of `:cmds`/`:fn` maps), and R285 Lua
# argparse (parser:option chain).  Glint's
# CPS-syntax-sugar approach uses Gleam's general-
# purpose `use` keyword to flatten what would
# otherwise be a deeply nested callback chain.
# Corpus's **first documented use-keyword-CPS CLI
# spec pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: gleepack uses **Glint
# subcommand path as Gleam list** at gleepack.gleam:
# 26-39 — `glint.add(at: ["targets", "available"],
# do: targets.available())` — the SUBCOMMAND PATH
# is a Gleam list of strings.  Two-element list
# `["targets", "available"]` means the command is
# invoked as `gleepack targets available`.  Glint
# supports ARBITRARY-DEPTH NESTING by extending
# the list.  Distinct from R296 Julia Comonicon
# (`@cast`-generated subcommand tree from nested
# namespaces), R301 Nim cligen (no built-in
# subcommand support — needs `dispatchMulti`),
# R302 Clojure babashka.cli (flat vector with
# longest-prefix `:cmds` matching).  Closest
# analog: cobra's `Command.AddCommand(...)` tree —
# but Glint uses a FLAT LIST (sister to R302
# babashka.cli's flat vector) rather than a TREE.
# Glint also supports `glint.path_help(at:, put:)`
# to attach a help string to an INTERMEDIATE NODE
# (like `targets`) that has no command body — see
# gleepack.gleam:33.  Documents the **flat-list-
# path-with-intermediate-help-strings CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: gleepack uses **Glint
# `strings_flag` for repeatable multi-value flags**
# at command/build.gleam:50 — `glint.strings_flag(
# "target")` parses `--target X` `--target Y`
# `--target Z` as a Gleam `List(String)`.  Distinct
# from `glint.string_flag` (single-string) and
# `glint.int_flag` (single-int).  Distinct from
# R296 Julia Comonicon's `Vector{String}` arg-type
# (positional-only), R285 Lua argparse `:args("*")`
# (positional-only), and R301 Nim cligen `seq[T]`
# (positional-only via type inference).  Glint's
# `strings_flag` is REPEATABLE FLAG (each `--target
# X` appends; sister to argparse's `action='append'`
# and clap's `Vec<String>` with `#[arg(num_args =
# 1.., action = ArgAction::Append)]`).  Corpus's
# **first documented Glint plural-flag-suffix-
# naming pattern** — Glint distinguishes
# `string_flag` vs `strings_flag` by NOUN PLURALITY
# in the function name.
#
# Critical extraction note: gleepack uses **Glint
# `glint.named_arg(...)` for typed positional
# arguments** at command/targets.gleam (add/remove
# subcommands) — `use slug <- glint.named_arg(
# "slug")` declares a NAMED POSITIONAL ARGUMENT.
# The `named` arg in the `glint.command` body's
# arity-3 callback `use named, _, _ <-` exposes a
# helper to retrieve named-positional values by
# name.  Distinct from R302 Clojure babashka.cli's
# `:args->opts [:script/lib]` (positional bound to
# named OPTION in the unified map), R301 Nim cligen
# (positional via `seq[int]` type at end of proc-
# param list), and R298 Pony's `positional` block
# (separate from `options` block).  Glint splits
# the command callback into THREE parameters:
# `(named, args, flags)` — `named` for named
# positionals declared via `named_arg`, `args` for
# overflow free-form positionals, `flags` for
# `--flag` values.  Corpus's **first documented
# triadic-callback CLI pattern (named/args/flags
# separation)**.
#
# Critical extraction note: gleepack uses **`glint.
# as_module` ESCRIPT mode flag** at gleepack.gleam:
# 24 — Glint supports TWO entry-point styles:
# `as_module` (Erlang ESCRIPT — `./gleepack args`)
# vs the implicit default (`gleam run -m gleepack
# -- args`).  `as_module` strips the redundant
# leading argv element that `gleam run -m` would
# prepend.  Distinct from R301 Nim cligen (no
# entry-point mode — compile-time `dispatch` macro
# is always-on), R302 Clojure babashka.cli
# (Babashka-specific `*file*` ↔ `babashka.file`
# main-guard at runtime).  Gleam's `as_module`
# explicitly signals which runtime convention
# applies.  Corpus's **first documented Gleam-
# specific entry-point-mode-flag CLI pattern**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_gleam` (Gleam compiler,
# already in corpus + blacklisted), `_iex` /
# `_livebook` / `_elixir` / `_mix` / `_hex` (all
# Elixir tools already in corpus), `_clojure-lsp` /
# `_cljfmt` / `_nbb` / `_shadow-cljs` / `_fennel` /
# `_janet` / `_hy` (Clojure family already in
# corpus), `_unison` (ships in stock zsh
# /opt/homebrew/share/zsh/functions/_unison —
# DUP), `_roc` / `_koka` / `_grain` / `_idris` /
# `_idris2` / `_mercury` / `_mlton` / `_polyml` /
# `_smlnj` / `_gnatmake` / `_valadoc` / `_vapigen`
# (exotic langs already in corpus).  Probed
# `birdie` (Gleam snapshot testing, 199 GH stars —
# uses HANDWRITTEN parser at birdie/internal/cli,
# NOT Glint; deferred for separate handwritten-
# parser-pattern round), `gleescript` (escript
# builder — minimal CLI surface), `pulsar`
# (Tkdefender88 static site gen, 1 star — too
# small), `bygg` (atomfinger Gleam initializr, 7
# stars — smaller surface than gleepack),
# `releam` (pedraal release tool, 0 stars — too
# new), `wisp/wrserver` (server-bootstrap, not a
# real CLI), `monitor_bear` (nerdyworm, narrow
# surface), `glinter` (pairshaped, linter — uses
# Glint but smaller subcommand tree), `nqcc_gleam`
# (hiphoox compiler-tutorial, 2 stars).  Chose
# gleepack: 10 GH stars, 9 SUBCOMMAND FILES with
# clean Glint surface (pipe-builder + use-syntax
# + strings_flag plural-naming + path_help group +
# named_arg positional + as_module escript mode),
# real packaged tool with hex.pm release, NESTED
# SUBCOMMAND TREE `targets {available, installed,
# add, remove, clean}` (exercises Glint's
# arbitrary-depth subcommand-path-as-list pattern),
# and EVERY MAJOR GLINT PATTERN represented in one
# repo.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

# gleepack subcommand tree decoded source-direct
# from src/gleepack.gleam:26-43 + each command
# file's glint.command_help text.  Subcommand order
# preserved from glint.add order at gleepack.gleam.
local -a gleepack_top=(
  'build:Build a standalone executable from your Gleam project'
  'run:Build and run your Gleam project using the native toolchain'
  'test:Run your Gleam project test suite'
  'dev:Build and run in dev/Debug mode (no executable produced)'
  'lustre/dev:Build and run lustre dev mode'
  'shell:Open a shell with the project environment loaded'
  'targets:Manage build targets (subcommand group)'
  'clean:Remove build artifacts'
  'version:Print the version of gleepack'
)
local -a gleepack_targets=(
  'available:List all supported target slugs'
  'installed:List targets installed in the local cache'
  'add:Download and install a target into the local cache'
  'remove:Uninstall a target from the local cache'
  'clean:Clear the entire target cache'
)

_arguments -C \
  '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[display gleepack help]' \
  '1: :->topcmd' \
  '*:: :->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  topcmd)
    _describe -t commands 'gleepack subcommand' gleepack_top && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $words[1] in
      build)
        # 3 flags from command/build.gleam:38-65 —
        # --output (string), --module (string),
        # --target (Glint strings_flag = repeatable
        # multi-value, represented in zsh as `*--`)
        _arguments -s -S \
          '--output=[where the built executable file will be written (default: ./build/$project_name)]:path:_files' \
          '--module=[module whose main function will be called (default: $project_name)]:module:' \
          '*--target=[build target (arch-os-runtime-version-extra; repeatable)]:target:' \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display build help]' && ret=0
        ;;
      run)
        # 2 flags from command/run.gleam:29-45
        _arguments -s -S \
          '--module=[module whose main function will be called]:module:' \
          '--target=[which target to run (must be a native target for the current platform)]:target:' \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display run help]' \
          '*::args to forward to the executable:' && ret=0
        ;;
      test|dev|lustre/dev|shell)
        # Each takes a single --target flag (per
        # respective command file)
        _arguments -s -S \
          '--target=[which target to use]:target:' \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display help]' && ret=0
        ;;
      targets)
        if (( CURRENT == 2 )); then
          _describe -t commands 'targets subcommand' gleepack_targets && ret=0
        else
          shift words
          (( CURRENT-- ))
          case $words[1] in
            add|remove)
              # Glint named_arg positional from
              # command/targets.gleam — required
              # `slug` argument
              _arguments -s -S \
                '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display help]' \
                '1:target slug (arch-os-runtime-version-extra):' && ret=0
              ;;
            available|installed|clean)
              _arguments -s -S \
                '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display help]' && ret=0
              ;;
          esac
        fi
        ;;
      clean|version)
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[display help]' && ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
